    correctIndex: 0,
    explanation: "A) Vancomycin — Correct. Vancomycin is the drug of choice for MRSA infection. It inhibits cell wall synthesis by binding to D-Ala-D-Ala terminus of peptidoglycan precursors (different mechanism from beta-lactams), so it remains effective against MRSA.\n\nB) Methicillin — Wrong. MRSA (Methicillin-Resistant S. aureus) is by definition resistant to methicillin and all other beta-lactam antibiotics due to altered PBP2a (encoded by mecA gene).\n\nC) Amoxicillin-clavulanate — Wrong. This is a beta-lactam/beta-lactamase inhibitor combination; MRSA resistance is not due to beta-lactamase but altered PBPs, so this combination is ineffective.\n\nD) Ceftriaxone — Wrong. All cephalosporins are ineffective against MRSA for the same reason as methicillin.",
    reference: "KD Tripathi 8th Ed, Chapter 52; Katzung 15th Ed.",
    difficulty: "Easy",
